{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"fab0576d-1fad-41a3-bd96-7cfdc9ad0a5c","content":"You're on MSTest 3.8.2 which supports constructor injection for `TestContext`. Here's the recommended pattern:\n\n```csharp\n[TestClass]\npublic class MyTests\n{\n    private readonly TestContext _testContext;\n    private MyService _service;\n\n    // Synchronous init: inject TestContext via constructor\n    public MyTests(TestContext testContext)\n    {\n        _testContext = testContext;\n    }\n\n    // Asynchronous init: use [TestInitialize] for async setup\n    [TestInitialize]\n    public async Task SetupAsync()\n    {\n        _service = await MyService.CreateAsync();\n    }\n\n    [TestMethod]\n    public void ExampleTest()\n    {\n        _testContext.WriteLine(\"Running test\");\n        Assert.IsNotNull(_service);\n    }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n- **Constructor** — for sync setup and `TestContext` injection (runs once per test)\n- **`[TestInitialize]`** — for `async` setup (`async Task` return type)\n- **`[ClassInitialize]`** — for one-time async setup shared across all tests in the class\n- Avoid putting async logic in the constructor; always use `[TestInitialize]` for that","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"1af46878-dee5-4ec5-ba0d-6ec7fc1eaa15","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"They're using MSTest 3.8.2 on .NET 9.0. In MSTest v3+, `TestContext` can be injected via constructor. Let me provide the recommended pattern.","outputTokens":358,"requestId":"602D:3F1DAE:250F4A8:27ADE0F:6A0311E5"},"id":"d590a6b4-de28-430d-ba39-c0e2d8adde06","timestamp":"2026-05-12T11:41:34.446Z","parentId":"ad9df192-d636-4432-a90d-c69791625ace"}
